Here's how to handle each scenario with MSTest:

## 1. Windows-Only Tests

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[OSCondition(OperatingSystems.Windows)]  // custom attribute approach
public void RegistryTest()
{
    if (!OperatingSystem.IsWindows())
        Assert.Inconclusive("Requires Windows");

    // Registry access here
}
```

Or use a simpler guard:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void RegistryTest()
{
    if (!RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.Windows))
    {
        Assert.Inconclusive("Windows only");
        return;
    }
    using var key = Registry.CurrentUser.OpenSubKey(@"Software\MyApp");
    Assert.IsNotNull(key);
}
```

## 2. Skip in CI (requires local GPU)

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GpuRenderTest()
{
    if (Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("CI") is not null)
        Assert.Inconclusive("Skipped in CI — requires local GPU");

    // GPU test logic
}
```

Or use a **test category** so CI can exclude it:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[TestCategory("RequiresGPU")]
public void GpuRenderTest() { /* ... */ }
```

Then in CI: `dotnet test --filter "TestCategory!=RequiresGPU"`

## 3. Flaky External API — Retry

MSTest doesn't have a built-in retry, but you can use `[DataRow]` tricks or a simple helper:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void WeatherApiTest()
{
    RetryHelper.Execute(maxRetries: 3, delay: TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2), () =>
    {
        var result = _weatherClient.GetForecast("Seattle");
        Assert.IsNotNull(result);
        Assert.IsTrue(result.Temperature > -100);
    });
}

// Helper
public static class RetryHelper
{
    public static void Execute(int maxRetries, TimeSpan delay, Action action)
    {
        for (int i = 0; i < maxRetries; i++)
        {
            try { action(); return; }
            catch when (i < maxRetries - 1)
            {
                Thread.Sleep(delay);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

## 4. Cleanup Even on Failure — `[TestCleanup]`

```csharp
[TestClass]
public class TempFileTests
{
    private string _tempFile = null!;

    [TestInitialize]
    public void Setup()
    {
        _tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();
    }

    [TestCleanup]  // Runs even if the test fails or throws
    public void Cleanup()
    {
        if (File.Exists(_tempFile))
            File.Delete(_tempFile);
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public void ProcessTempFile()
    {
        File.WriteAllText(_tempFile, "test data");
        var result = MyProcessor.Process(_tempFile);
        Assert.AreEqual("expected", result);
    }
}
```

## Summary

| Scenario | Approach |
|---|---|
| OS-specific | `Assert.Inconclusive()` guard or `--filter` |
| Skip in CI | Check `CI` env var or `[TestCategory]` + filter |
| Flaky API | Retry helper (loop + catch) |
| Cleanup | `[TestCleanup]` — always runs post-test |

`Assert.Inconclusive()` marks the test as **skipped** (not failed), which is the idiomatic MSTest way to conditionally skip at runtime.
